I need it in the slide notes.  I can't remember all the details over 2 days -- I need notes!

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
I think the wording in the test is unnecessarily complex. Questions that use System in the question around Demo where Solution might be the answer for example or the test question around what is not a principle for Lean Portfolio Management a lot of questions seem oddly structured and the answers, while similar to the book and online resources are just a touch different. This will be very complex for learners are are not "english first". 

Also, I appreciate the practice test.  I felt I could only take it partially as I didn't want to lose access to it before I was ready.  I think you should change this. 

Because I took the test multiple times, but only 60% of it at a time, the results didn't acurately indicate what I should study. 

Because I took the test multiple times, but only 60% of it at a time. I become quite familiar with the questions.  I scored a 92% on the practice test when I took the whole thing, but only 77% on the actual test and I know many people who scored in the high 80s% on the practice test and failed the actual test. I am not sure it is a good forecast of success.

Additional_Comments__c: The exam is timed, and I had accidentally closed out of the exam.The timer was still ticking during the time I exited the exam. Additional_Comments__c: The exam thoroughly represented the SAFe Agile website content but the questions asked were not necessarily represented by the course content.  The course content - through hands-on activities - walked us through actually implementing SAFe - which was very good and useful.  But I could not have passed that exam based on the course book and the course content alone - I absolutely had to go back and read, study and memorize the chapters/articles in the study guide that reside on the website.  That should be emphasized by the instructors - that the class and class book are only one component of what the exam will be based off of and self study and reading of the website must also happen.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
I have to take this test while at work, I don't have a 2 hr time span that is not interrupted; this makes the 2 hr time limit almost impossible to make. 

I would like to review the actual questions I missed with the correct answer displayed. The test is created using a bank of questions so there really is no reason this can't be done.

Also don't close the practice test when we hit a 70%; that's not high enough to feel comfortable in passing the actual test. Leave it open so we can study until we feel ready. When we take the practice test change the questions up so we aren't retaking the same test in a different order. We remember the answer not from learning but because we know the question. Mix it up and give a REAL practice test.

In the book given for the class, PRINT THE ENTIRE BOOK! There are links in pages 20 layers deep, it's very easy to get lost in all of it. Print it all out and place it in the book where it belongs. This way we can read, highlight and study the entire book without the distraction of all the links that may or may not have to do with the portion we are working on.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: Honestly, I have taken and successfully completed many classes and certifications, both online and direct presence; this class and it's training materials would come very close to last as far as getting any kind of graded results. The support folks deserve an "A"; however the actual content of the class- when compared to the actual testing - fails in comparison- to actually being any kind of preparation training for your testing. Your training course should be geared towards not only learning the material but ALSO passing the tests. It's content should cover both and be presented during the class, not left for massive self study on endless pages off the web.The trainer was friendly, and seemed well informed, but far too much of the actual Learning process, was left up to the students themselves (through no fault of the trainer) who already had full time jobs . I'd recommend a complete restructure of the training to match not only the Content of the class but the format of the Test, to the testing encountered. This is not inexpensive training we are paying for, we should at the very least walk away from a class with the educational exposure and materials we need to pass any given testing on a subject we have been "trained" on.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
In principle the material is good. What disappointed me a lot during the Implementing SAFe training and Exam preparation are two things:
 (1) There is no single comprehensive slide set/pdf to walk through for the preparation. You are recommended to study the training slides and additionally the articles on the webpage and this means that you have to read a lot of redundant information. So the learning efficiency is low
 (2) One of the SAFe principles we were taught during the training is to Build incrementally with fast, integrated learning cycles. How can you do so, if you are not sure whether your understanding is correct or not? Neither the test exam nor the real one is really telling you what you understood and answered wrongly. I fully understand, that you do not want to disseminate the answers to your exam questions but you must offer a better way to improve the understanding than simply to state "Read SPC Section xyz again" as it is done via the "Additional Information" after the (test) exam

Additional_Comments__c:
This comment is related to courseware:  It is commonly understood that SAFe courses at the practitioner level are largely created to facilitate learning for employees of an organization, who attend these workshops as "teams".  Due to this I suggest that you revisit the concept of story pointing "as 1 point per developer day" to calculate initial velocity. A better approach to calculate initial velocity is actually tasking, and aligning it with capacity.  By doing so, when you introduce story pointing / and the games with dogs in it.... it makes sense.

Thankyou for reading through my recommendation
With regards
Rajeswari (Raji)

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
Most SAFe teams and orgs get bogged down in all the seemingly prescriptive mechanics at the expense of the outcomes SAFe is supposed to help deliver. This is not the fault of SAFe, but rather the "coaches" that impose it. And it's beginning to give SAFe a very bad name. An SPC cert should mean something; SPC cert exams should be proctored and should delve far more deeply into organizational change management, practical application and all successive levels of Bloom's Taxonomy. Perhaps add an essay section which must be scored by SAI employees. I would also add a personality test element to score a potential SPC's level of genuine empathy and ability to work collaboratively/consultatively in order to successfully overcome real-world organizational impediments without imposing prescriptive/destined-to-fail solutions.

SAI could probably add some more change management elements to the courseware as well; they could more frequently, more explicitly, and more thoroughly call out antipatterns along with suggestions to avoid and/or overcome them; and it would be great to address the elephant in the room: Pournelle's Law of Bureaucracies.

The successful case studies are great, but most companies presently adopting SAFe will never make that list of successful case studies. Perhaps embrace a little radical candor and include some SAFe war stories (even if the companies are just "hypothetical examples") along with some explanations why they've struggled and suggestions for overcoming these types of struggles.

I would also love to see some more team dynamics and contemporary leadership material added to the SAFe for Teams and Scrum Master classes. I believe there is value in teams understanding things like psychological safety, belongingness, the need to embrace healthy dissent, and the educational value of failures, etc.

It would be great if SAFe would recommend the decoupling of "feature points" from "story points" (better yet, don't estimate features in points) and to incorporate a story map-type element to near-term product roadmaps.

Since no one can possibly identify every story, dependency, all acceptance criteria, unexpected additional defect fixes, integration complications, or the impact of oft-overlooked factors such as increased employee attrition during a SAFe adoption, long-term estimates can't possibly be correct without extrapolating and accounting for inevitable variability from past empirical data (and praying that it doesn't increase). Yet these all factors lead to hidden scope creep (which everyone incorrectly blames others for) and cause programs to delay deliveries, impose the same old death marches at the end of PIs, and/or suffer from any number of additional dysfunctions.

Again, it would be nice to see some real-world guidance on overcoming these challenges. At the very least, before receiving an SPC certification, a candidate should be able to demonstrate an ability to identify these variables and the types of thought-provoking questions and subtle suggestions that can help his or her employer start looking in the right direction for potential solutions.

I am proud that SAFe certifications have real value today; however, if nothing changes soon, I am afraid that value will rapidly diminish to near-zero.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
I don't like the label for the 'Program' level in SAFe. It leads to two kinds of confusion in my conversations:
1. Traditional project and program managers might associate this with traditional program management constructs, which are temporary and fit for unique assignments rather that BAU (business as usual). And SAFe is e framework designed to make change business as usual.
2. Software developers might associate it with a single software program, rather than a system of numerous applications, and hardware components.

I would suggest the word 'Product' as it aligns with the Product Owner role at this level. And a (large) solution may consist of several products.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: After taking the class the instructor told us we would need an additional 3 hours of studying. After reviewing learning plan and following it, the time I spent reading additional material far exceeded 3 hrs. Instructors should be more explicit about the actual time required. Having practice exams without the correct answers are a waste of time. Although I reviewed practice tests multiple times and looked for incorrect answers in materials, there are some that I could not find and am still unsure of, additionally, the actual test is far more detailed then what the class reviews. Some of the questions in the test focus on the drawings within materials or minute details within materials. Again, given what we were told/taught in class and the practice tests instructors should provide more guidance in this space. Some learn by taking practice tests, getting questions wrong and by reviewing the correct answers...thereby learning the material. Its unfortunate that your question pool is probably small and does not provide the ability for this kind of learning.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: While I received excellent customer service, I must say I am not as pleased with the way the certification exam is conducted. Feedback for "learning" is, at best, sparse. While I may be one of the oldest to ever attempt to become an SPC I am a life-long learner. The way the 'training' is conducted and the test implemented does not give me hope we can implement SAFe in our corner of the Federal Government. I want to be a great change agent and am continuing to read and learn but have been unsuccessful in passing the practice test. Knowing what section (which does NOT correspond to the workbook as you indicate) I need to review is not helpful. I understand this is not a regurgitation of useless sayings and data, but it isn't helpful when you think you have it right but don't know for sure. At this time I may be giving you kudos for the customer service I requested, but I will not be telling others to join in the quest for real agility nor will I be advocating the use of the particular company for ANY training or partnering.

You want to develop confident scrum master that reflect well on Scaled Agile's version of agile? Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: The support team guy was great !  He answered my question, knew there was a system issue and suggested I tell you about the poor training/testing questions.  Scaled Agile process/website, testing, practice testing absolutely sucked.  It is absolutely useless to have a practice test that does not tell you which questions you missed much less what the right answer is and why or where the source answer can be found.  Saying you missed something in a section is absolutely counter-productive because it only frustrates the user rather than assisting them in learning the material that you believe they should know/understand.  Additionally, writing test questions which refer to things the instructor SHOULD HAVE said is only useful if you can guarantee the instructors use those terms when explaining the process or concept.  Users can not be expected to extrapolate information from undefined terms.  GEMBA is not the same as "visualizing work" and GEMBA was never defined by the instructors in my training course;  so either test for GEMBA or put "visualizing work" beside GEMBA in the training materials.  This was a very poorly written test question and certainly needed to be part of the training if it is so important to that pillar in the process.  And if it is so important to the concept, why is it the 3rd item and not the first item?

The quiz was more difficult than it should be if you do not know what to focus upon.  If you want people to be successful, provide answers so that we may know where we fall short and where additional study needs to be done. 

The book provided has no index, no real lexicon, no table of contents hence trying to understand is difficult.   Preparing for the quiz was like shooting in the dark.  

Now I have to do the same for the exam and pay $50.00.  I am wondering if this is really worth it?

Having developed and instructed training courses for adults in the U.S. Air Force and the private sector, I would encourage providing more so that working people may pass the exam.

I've several times had to provide updates to my boss that I'm 'waiting on a response from SAFe' which has happened with enough frequency that I've heard "So what else is new?" when giving a report out. Anyway, it's not a showstopper but SAFe's success has made it a vital tool for many practitioners and it seems to be run more like 'side hustle' for SAFe rather than it's core business.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: This is more of a comment on the overall quality of the materials and the site itself, vs support per se.  I'm an SPC that has been giving the SAFe for Teams 4.6 materials to large groups.  There are numerous errors in the slide deck and booklet.  There are also lots of issues when learners go to access their Learning Plans and take the practice tests.  They're either not getting any results or just the % and no feedback on the particular sections they did well or poorly on.  They are using Chrome with a cleared cache and when they escalate to Support, it's a canned response that comes back asking which browser they're using (even though it was stated in the original email).  Very poor customer service experience and it's starting to degrade the reputation of SAFe and Scaled Agile at my company, which is unfortunate and will make my job as a change agent infinitely more challenging.  Please do more proof-reading of your materials before they're published and when errors are brought to light, fix them and get new materials out ASAP!

Additional_Comments__c:
Today I would like to give a feedback on the preparation and the SPC itself: I really practiced a lot a have read almost all material in advance because I took and still take the task of accompanying the change in the SAFe way very seroius. 
First, my observation during preparation is, that from a certain level of practicing the results of my practice test did not change (82 or 83%). The feedback given to me was not valuable because it didn' give any hint what was wrong. So the was only little room for improvement. 
Second, for several questions, I could not even find an answer in the material.
Third, the practice test is only kind of a 30-50%-preparation for the real exam, because the questions in th exam are very much different (a higher-sphisticated quality of formulation) from the style in the practice test.
So, my enthusiam on the way this preparation for the test is limited.
I think, I can judge this a little bit, because I am also professor for systems theory at university.
Therefore, I think additional 250$ is really disappointing.

Thank you!

Hello,

One comment about my request which related to changing my email address. In order to avoid anyone stealing the ID of another Scaled Agile Community Member I would recommend your support would ask additional questions to verify the identity. For example you could ask email address, phone number, account name (if separate from email address), time when certification was previously performed, known certificate ID, etc. E.g. verifying the person asking the email address (or similar ID change) is really the correct person. And naturally these things should be ones that are not easily gathered from social media.

Just a recommendation :) Otherwise good and fast help.

Br
Miska

I wish I had better warning messages from Scaled Agile to let me know that my certification would be of no use unless I upgraded it to the latest SA4.6 version. I am so lost without help when I heard that I am now forced to take classes and spend $1000 to get back to the current version. 
The fact that I didn't need to take classes to get certified for SA4.6 if I had upgraded my SA3.0 to SA4.5 during last year (using the upgrade path provided by Scaled Agile in the web)  tells me that classes can't be the only to upgrade to SA4.6 if you miss the interim upgrade. Missing to upgrade to SA4.5 should not affect my ability to upgrade to SA4.6 :(

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
This is the Information Age - where exponential technological innovation is driving acceleration.  "Agile" methods are just common sense, with age-old wisdom of valuing people and communications.   We have digital tools and DevOps that are enabling us to be agile.  Development teams do not see anything advanced about planning iterations using post it notes.  The challenge is to get teams to really collaborate (and not compete). The challenge is to overcome our social and cultural biases (men/women treating each other as equals in the workforce.) The struggle is to remove the insecurities that teams have about being outsourced or displaced by younger talent (fresh out of college.).  There is no time to learn new skills on the job, you have to hit the ground running.
That said, I will continue to pay $100 a year - to "stay certified".

Additional_Comments__c:
Commercial background of the method is extreme (On my point of view a clear negative point of SAFe(R) - in comparison to other "Agile method provider/workframes explainers".):

- A lot of Certificates with low difference between each other.
- Timeframed taking of the certification - within 1 month after the course - quite aggressive.
- Learning withoud immediate feedback (is the target to not give the full transparency while learning?)
- Course slides are not appropriate for learning. (Webpage content is good/exellent, but not in a "bookform" version available.)
Recurring "recertification" only possible with payment of a fee.
- Ongoing retension/amelioration of the workframe ist exellent: The dependency on the version certification ist - on the other hand - too high.
- Webpage with the (take the test) ist missleading! (Afer a chat it has been resettet for me: Exellent service, thanks again! The answer was: "It happens all the time." -> Something has to be changed.)

I am looking forward to be am member of SAFe(R) community. (Even for a short period of time, as my emplower doesn't pay recurrent fees for re-certifications.)

Cheers, Gabriele Broggini

Additional_Comments__c:
I have worked SAFe for about 3 years.  It has improved our production of new products ten fold.  My only complaint is that someone needs to seriously look at how you get certified.  

First, you offer the free exam right after the training.  There is no way anyone knows SAFe 60 days after the training.  So the free offer is of no use.

Second, it is a lot of information to learn, so to change the context of the questions is absolutely to most absurd idea yet.

The consensus in the business world is that it is a great program however extremely hard and expensive to get certified.

I have heard many groups make the decision to not adopt SAFE and just continue with Agile Scrum.

GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: I had to forward this to my personal email address because I couldn't open the link from my work address. I would not recommend SAFe to anyone. I think it's a racket. The language you use is jargon. The concepts erudite. It's like reading an academic paper about inorganic chemistry. Why make this so hard? Did you get guidance from real people or consultants? I don't think you practice what you preach at all. The practice test is in no way reflective of the real test. The study guide provides no guidance at all. The only reason I'm doing this is because it's the framework my company adopted. I assure you that if I ever go to another company I would never, ever recommend SAFe in its current state. If I get the opportunity to influence a change to a more accessible framework, I'd do it in a heartbeat.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: The certifications exams have very confusing questions. It should not be that complicated. The questions should be around multiple topics and should be based on understanding. but not putting confusing answers out of 4 two are three looks correct. Specially DevOps certification exam has lot of conusing answers, it has 4 quadrants with 3/4 sub segments in each quarter, so total 12+ areas are there. For any person it is difficult to remember where a particular thing lies. If a person fails he has to take exam by paying $50, you can make money in that way, so you might have designed the exams like that. But many will not be interested to pay $50 for 1yr certification., So you will be losing customers and will loose interest in your SAFe certifications. Mine is best example, I failed the SAFe for Teams, but never took that exam again as I need to pay $50 for that kind of exam, where answers are confusing rather than knowledge based. Its up to you how you design your certification exams but as a customer/user I am giving my feedback.

Additional_Comments__c:
There are far too many errors on exam, such as the exam changing answers itself covertly.

Found an exam question that did not provide the correct answer found easily in the Scaled Agile POPM workbook. Had to pick a random answer for DevOps since correct answer not available. 

Practice exams in NO WAY prepare the user for the actual tests. Also, since no question, or same caliber of question, is repeated in the certification exams, I see zero harm in providing the correct answers for questions missed. This is a course for learning, correct?  Feels more like a course meant to trick people, which is the antithesis of what should be the goal. 

The exam goals appear to be designed NOT to teach/train, but to deceive and collect money. If it were meant to teach, the user would be eventually provided the correct answers for missed questions to learn from AND validate the test's accuracy. (Transparency was a major focus of training, but this course obscures transparency by not providing the correct answers eventually).

I know that a lot of changes have been implemented lately, but it's been a bit too much to fast.  We are all struggling to learn.  I have a couple issues still to mention. 

1.  Not all teams work over the weekends but Rally still counts Sat/Sun as working days.  It would be good to have a toggle that the teams can set to eliminate counting those days in Cycle Time for teams that don't work weekends.  I'm sure there are a lot. 
2. The Cycle Time Extract is not extracting the data for the To date.   Example, if I add from 1/9/2019 to 5/9/2019, it won't pick up the completed user stories for the 9th of May.   If I change that to the 10th, it picks them up. 

Keep up the good work on this system and we'll all be happy!

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
2 main reasons why I wouldn't recommend.   First, Agile does a very poor job around transitioning and for the first several months, if not year+, Agile creates more work.  None of the ceremonies actually reduce the number of meetings needed and the casual approach on documentation and requirements only complicates future changes making them slower and more costly. 

Second reason is the exam and certification process.  The practice tests and final exams never show what answers were wrong so there's no opportunity to learn and grow.  The little feedback that is provided is the absolute bare minimum.  Even the hardest college classes I've taken showed, at a minimum, which questions were incorrect.  The process Agile currently has in place only ensures that whatever concepts I failed to understand in the class and while studying, I will continue to fail to understand after being certified.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: I was mid examp for my SAFE certificate when the system went down for maintenance and did not automatically return. Resulting in a ~ 70% completed exam, marked as a fail and lost. Consideration should be given to customers outside the US and a better approach to maintenance should surely be considered. I emailed at the point this happened (tuesday) and again to chase on the weds, thurs,friday......I got a helpful reply on the monday which explained that the team had been in PI planning session, that reply reset my exam with no timeframe which is positive and I have since passed. But a. it means I have had to retake an exam I was 70% through and Ive had to wait a week and therefore re-prepare...not very agile. The online BOT on the site is constantly showing for me as offline? ...I dont know if that is configuration at my end or an issue.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: I've submitted about 5 or 6 support tickets in the past.  In each of these I had to follow up with additional email.   I keep getting the same feedback (we're really busy)..    From the leadership perspective, SLAs etc are really important.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
IMO Access to support thru e-mail/voicemail isn't sufficient when testing servers are post 'maintenance' responses in the middle of the day while tests are in progress. 

No guidance and a lot of stress.

I'd suggest a mechanism to post notifications when there are issue that can be reported. The welcome page and login page remained accessible during the outage.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
I love SAFe and the team. However, in this instance, from a customer viewpoint, Scaled Agile failed completely. 

I'm booked for a training session and I can't get the materials. I can't chat or contact anyone at SAFe through the website nor phone call. I send an URGENT request for trainer help and you respond several days later on the day of the class???? Because you have PI Planning???!!

I'm all for PI Planning being inclusive, but to abdicate all customer support? I might have had to show up for class and say I can't get the materials from Scaled Agile because they have PI Planning so class will be delayed a day? Not to mention not being able to prepare for class with the latest materials. How would that go over for my career? Very disappointing. 

Hopefully this is a one off and I can continue to have full confidence in and fully support SAFe and Scaled Agile going forward.

Your password reset/unlock process is terrible.  There was no easy way for me to reset my password.  I had to send an email to a support group.  That wasn't that easy either.  I finally reset my password and got in.  Then about 6 hours later I went to reenter the sight.  I'm now locked out again, and after only one try of getting in I receive a page that tells me I am locked out and I can't even retry a 2nd time to log in.  

"You are temporarily locked out
You have been temporarily locked out of this system. This means that you will not be able to log in for a while."

It is not acceptable that it is this hard and difficult.  I wish my enterprise picked another Agile vendor with better tooling.  I can't explain how frustrating this is.  

SIGH

What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
The following comment has to do with the online training materials and is focused at the POPM course. 

Part of my training is as a professional educator in elementary, middle school and high school. 

Regardless of the fact that SAFe Agile has progressed through different iterations, inconsistencies and reuse of language describing similar but not exact knowledge points create a foggy understanding that cannot be unraveled with certitude. Great effort was expended and a collection of over 500 pages of notes from the online material was collected. Perhaps that is the difficulty! 

I took the test exam three times. I took the certification exam three times. After each exam, I focused exactly on answering the test questions that I had trouble with. On the test exam I plateaued at 80% and again on the certification at 76%. On the limited data I had available from the tests and results provided (I did not receive and could not get from tech support the data from the 2nd cert test) no specific guidance could be gleaned for the generalized percentage categories and also numerical analysis did not reveal which questions were missed.

Categorization of questions in the question bank is not made available therefore making the reviewing task even more difficult. Many of the questions could not easily be categorized inductively due to cross-domain interference.

My personal education contains a Master of Sciences degree in a technology field with honors. I have been responsible for creating testing materials and setting up question banks for automated testing in seven states. I personally have been responsible for teams to create automated testing software. One system that I owned was in continuous use for twenty-seven years.


Given the level of effort that I invested in the POPM course, I expected to achieve at least 90%. I diligently studied after each test using my nearly photographic recall of each question's gist and content to review again and again.


So, my conclusion is that I am poorly equipped to grasp your materials using the methods of knowledge acquisition that I have honed over the last 40 years. Using the online materials only is inadequate due to the inconsistencies accumulated over years of revisions and an inability to clearly differentiate knowledge points.

Next time I'll buy a book (if an electronic version is available)!

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: Our account exec, Leslie Tillman, has bent over backwards to try to help us so kudos to her.  I also understand that last week was the annual Global Summit but that doesn't mean everyone using your product suddenly stops needing support.  To make matters worse, our client is a Fortune 100 client.  The department we're supporting is the first in a wave of divisions that want to do Agile Transformation.  The support they receive on this engagement will influence decisions they make on what approach to use for other divisions.  Saying the only way to get support is via a webform and hope/prayers we get a timely response is a horrible approach to customer service.  If we upgraded our partnership, is it like Frequent Flier programs where we'd get better support?  I'm already pushing my leadership to upgrade and that might help a little but my experience with the service needs has been really, really bad.
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: Either provide a phone number to talk to someone or pick up the phone and call the person back who submitted the ticket.  So much time is wasted going back and forth in emails asking for a description of the issue because "we were not able to replicate the issue you're seeing" when a quick phone call and possibly a screen share via WebEx, Skype, Teams- whatever- would show the support personnel exactly what we're seeing.  I'm not asking them to fix a problem they see but what I am actually experiencing.  It's absolutely horrible to have a client I'm trying to support ask what the status is and the best I can offer is "I submitted a ticket to their support desk via the website and they're saying I can expect a response 'typically in 1-2 business days.'  So far I haven't talked to a single person- like, actually talked to someone- and it's been a week since I submitted my tickets.  Some issues were resolved but without any explanation of when the work was performed, what was done to fix my issue or what new issues the "fix" has created that still doesn't allow me to do my job.  I get that responding to a trouble ticket with a "we can't replicate your issue, please respond with more detail/screenshots" allows you to place your ticket in "awaiting customer response" thereby stopping the SLA clock on response time but that doesn't help me, the customer, at all.  What's worse than me being frustrated?  My client who chose Scaled Agile being frustrated that I can't get the support I need to support them.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: I had two tickets and I've already provided a pretty detailed response to the other survey request.  When clients have critical needs, submitting a webform and waiting for someone to respond is absolutely horrible.  I still haven't actually talked to anyone- everything has been sent via email so the process is just so long- Day 1 submit webform, day 3/4 get an email back acknowledging there's an issue with an "assurance" that I will be responded to 'typically in 1-2 business days', Day 6 get a response that doesn't solve the issue so email back that the response doesn't resolve the issue, day 7 get an email back that the issue has been escalated and will be responded to 'typcially within 1-2 business days', Day 9 get an email that the issue has been resolved or 'sorry but that functionality is not currently available and we hope to have it at some point in the future' with no actual explanation on how I deal with the need to perform that function in the future.
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: Provide a number to call to talk to someone rather than a webform, call people back to acknowledge the issue and talk through resolution or atleast the steps being taken to resolve, provide an explanation of what was done to resolve the issue, provide feedback that matches actual capability, commit to timelines for response rather than "typically within 1-2 business days"

I asked for Benji to share my email thread with his supervisor. 
I experienced an issue that prevented me from taking the practice exam / certification exam during the time I had blocked on my calendar.  Basically, I didn't need excuses. These things happen - I just needed an efficient follow-up. I asked that the date extended. I asked for 30 days due to the Thanksgiving holiday and other commitments. I was given 2 weeks.  Also, I had included that same request for my 2 colleagues. We took the class at the same time and planned to walk through a practice exam so I knew they were impacted.  I requested they receive that they be given extensions. The response to my email did not include them (they were cc'ed when I replied to SA) and I was told that they needed to request directly.  I was not impressed. Not very customer focused.

What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
My test was interrupted approximately 6 times, making it very hard to take and complete. It kept putting questions in front of me that I'd already answered, totally making me second-guess my answers and really made me feel like it wasn't going to register my test properly at all. I do feel that it interrupted my concentration and abbreviated my opportunity to pass the test. I really feel like it would be fair for me to be able to take the test again at no cost as this was definitely a less than ideal test-taking situation. 

The response I got back from customer service didn't even address this request and just told me it must have been my internet. I felt dismissed. And since I don't have alot of control in making anything better, I feel at a loss and as a result will likely let my colleagues know that they should NOT try to certify as I don't feel like I've gotten a fair shake and the system doesn't work well. 

PLEASE HEAR ME when I say this - another colleague of mine took the test at the SAME time on the other side of the country and the same thing happened to her - I do NOT think it's possible that we just happened to have simultaneous internet problems in different locations. I DO feel that it was your system and a capacity issue, or possibly an internet problem on your end. Is there any chance of retaking the test at no cost?

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: I love SAI and the method, but believe you should follow what you are teaching.
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
It was much easier, efficient, and timely for me to speak with someone rather than send an email.  Email further extends the communication between two people.  As we teach, we value face to face communication, and when not possible, something as close to it as possible.  Email is not close to face to face communication, at all.  

Making the people who support and are the very lifeblood of SAI go through a model that delays communication does not follow the models of communication suggested by the methodology.   

I would much prefer to talk with someone in person.  Give us live people to talk with when we have an issue to work through.  It may be more efficient for you to work through email, but in this, you are putting all the burden on those who support you.

Expecting me to pay $3K for a certification course, upgrade to 5.0 a couple of months later, and then ask me to spend another $3K for the same course just to get an updated 5.0 book ... really? I'm really not trying to be snarky with this response but this really happened to me and it was very offensive to think that Scaled Agile would be ... greedy (can't think of a more diplomatic way to say it).  I believe it will be resolved soon when the PDF is sent.  Maybe you also ought to proactively offer this as a download for SPC5 upgraded consultants in good standing.  We are out there on the front-line as your evangelists.

As one of the prime lean/agile change leaders at the Volvo Group I have a constant issue with replying to people wandering how much Scaled Agile is in it for the money. When I myself now can't get a good answer on why my SPC-certification seems to be prolonged with one year from the date I pay the fee and not with one year from the date it is due (as you yourself state at your site), I lose trust in you! Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
On 01/27, 2020, I submitted 3 questions (support tickets 00229754, 00229846, 00229849)  within 5 hours. For each one, I received an automatic response with a ticket number almost immediately. 

On 02/01, 2020, you sent me 2 requests to rate my interaction with the Scale Agile support team. Since none of the request contains any of the original ticket numbers, I first thought I had no way what I should rate. 

Looking again at the automatic response for ticket #00229849, I noticed that it also contained a quite obscure reference number at the bottom: [ref:_00Dd0fJSp._5000W1YIPeb:ref]. Searching for this reference number in your request for feedback, I finally found a portion of it buried in the requests HTML source code for the actual buttons, if only partly (Case_ID=5000W00001YIPebQAH).

You actually RESOLVED my problem by correcting the content of a web page (but without updating that page's modification date at the bottom!), but then you make your customer jump through hoops in recognizing what you did.

I strongly recommend you make this process of tracing support cases much easier - even if you assume that nobody ever submits several tickets within a short timeframe.

Additional_Comments__c: Y'all provide a great product - backed up with tons of readily available information.  Not to mention, you have versions!  While everything else under the agile sun stays the same SAI has thoughtfully said, "we update all the time.  We version up when there are significant changes.  Our certification version up as well."  Not stagnant, relevant.  I love it.  If I still lived in Colorado I'd want to come work with all of you.  When you're ready to open a satellite location in Birmingham, AL let me know.  :-)
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: The enablement test I was taking crashed mid-way through.  This was very concerning obviously so I'm frantically looking for tech support on the community.scaledagile.com site.  I started with the "Chat With Support" option but it only yields answers based on what is already typed up in the FAQ.  Disappointing, because you assume "chat with support" isn't just a bot, but a real person.  Then I start looking for a real "contact support" option.  It wasn't listed at the bottom in the links, nor on the top nav menu.  I thought surely it would be under the "more" menu but nope.  I just happened to try clicking on my name thinking, maybe I saw it there when I updated my profile.  And there it was.  I understand not wanting people to email support right away for every issue, but I also didn't expect a scavenger hunt.  My 2 cents, that type of crash should have something more specific listed in terms of the issues and options for support.  The wording on the error message made it appear that my company was causing the issue, not that there was an issue on the SAI side.

What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
Try to find fair solutions for those who support the framework, but are not yet partner. In my case: I have for each Trainer enablement purchased a single license to have access towards the content in between the next trainings. Due to the Upgrade from 4.6 to 5.0 I need to purchase again those licenses. That is quite a greedy behavior-as my company is not yet partner, my old licenses are useless for now (I can convert them towards 5.0, but can only download 4.6 content) - as my company only reemburses licenses which are on one single invoice. I will not reimbursed for licenses I already obtained.
As a result of this questionable behavior I canceled my trip to the SAFe Summit and I will consider to stop supporting SAFe.

What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
Everything about my recent interaction with Scaled Agile was incredibly difficult. My company has a Silver Partnership with Scaled Agile, and the on-boarding process was ridiculous. It took at least a week to get set up as the Super Admin. Then, I couldn't administrate any of our classes only to be told later that I needed to be the Account Admin as well. That process took another week. 

The overall criticism that I have is that there was no follow-through with the support. No one who assisted me asked for a comprehensive understanding of what we needed accomplished. And, in spite of my explanations, it seemed no one had the time, knowledge, or willingness to fully on-board me and my team to the platform.

Amit

What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
I was disappointed, as Scaled Agile was not really answering my question, but rather looking for a way to answer my question in a one sentwnce answer to be done with it. In my opinion that is contradicting to what Scaled Agile teaches in its courses, when it comes to interaction. I asked for a specific set of trainings (given that all precinditions are met) and i was being made aware of the preconditions. It seems to me that my request was not carefully being read. That makes me feel not being taken seriously and disrespected.
Making it easier to handle my issue is therefore quite easy: dont make me feel bad! Read my email and dont just fly over it to be able to say "yes its answered, next" and finally answer the actual question that was my request! 

To come to your next question: i will recommend Scaled Agile, but not your support, so please also understand the next rating only to be applicable of using the email adress i wrote to in the fist place

Additional_Comments__c: I quite like the upgrade path you have done.   its a good idea.   However, there needs to be a way to upgrade not just from 4, but from earlier certs. What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: I was told there was nothing I could do to upgrade my SAFe v3 agilist cert.  don't leave behind folks who have SAFe v3 certs. Other certification bodies do not have this; agile alliance, scrum.org etc. all you do is pay your money and renew.    the upgrade requirements were not advertised or made clear. Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c: You should also think about redesigning your exams.  I understand that you want to make them difficult so that the SAFe certifications mean something.  That makes sense and I value that.  The part I don't like is that it feels like the questions are designed to trick you instead of test your knowledge.   I'm not the only one that feels this way.  75% of the people I talk to that have taken your exams feel this way.  I find that I'm reading the questions 3 to 4 times to make sure that I am answering correctly.  I take an exam, pass the test, and am left  feeling more angry at the way the questions are written than a sense of accomplishment for passing the exam.
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
I'm not fond of the way Scaled Agile handles license purchases.  I am a certified SPC4 and was trying to purchase licenses so a SPC certified ICON consultant could offer a SAFe Scrum Master class.  I couldn't purchase the licenses because I hadn't completed the enablement for the Scrum Master class.  I wasn't teaching the class.  I was buying licenses so our high priced ICON consultant didn't have to spend his time buying licenses and uploading rosters.  
This also causes problems with license management on our side.  Now I have licenses purchased on my account for last year's Leading SAFe, the ICON consultant has license history on his account, and our past ICON consultant has licenses on his account.  To find out what AmFam has purchased for licenses I have to go to 3-4 different accounts instead of having it centralized.  I also have one unused Leading SAFe license on my account that I could not re-assign because I couldn't buy licenses without spending about a day's worth of time on the Scrum Master enablement.  Frustrating and inconvenient.  I get that Scaled Agile wants to ensure that those teaching are up-to-date on course enablement but then couldn't you stop the download of the training materials to those that haven't completed the course enablement?  Seems to me like Scaled Agile has optimized for it's policies and made life more difficult for their customers.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
(1) I am thrilled with the increased and improved content, rigor and (increasingly) people-centric (including "business") direction of SAFe. It's a weighty investment of time and $ (I paid for my SPC Workshop 6 years ago and give up billable time to attend. All but 1 renewal, too. VERY cost-effective investments and thought-provoking, too.)

(2) There's a perception (I hear often) that SAFe is too cumbersome, too formal and too rigid. (This is coming from coaches and trainers I categorize as too formal and rigid...but they repeat these comments to others, too.) Being able to "filter" The Big Picture (online) has helped a bit. What we're addressing (enterprise and/or business agility) is also often described as cumbersome and (in need of) formal methods (as recently as yesterday on a webinar with some @thinker50 consultants.) I think you/we could do more to make SAFe more appealing.
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: Allow me (the trainer, in this "issue") to change the dates of my remote course (and have the CMS alert your team) versus me calling or writing your team to inform them. All that said...I am very happy with the current arrangement!

Priority:  Took the 5.0, and the back button was not available on the test.  I typically go to all the questions I am sure of and then go back to finish the questions that I am most challenged with, unlike the other exams, this test did not have a back button. It was completely eliminated, which was a flaw on your website.   I have requested you reset this test for me but no one has responded to me.   

Please respond to Loretta_Cole@tjx.com to let me know if you intend to reset the test. 

Lower Priority:  I was taking the Scrum Master Exam and the web site crashed.  By the time I was able to get on again, the clock was still ticking and lost valuable time and didn't have time to finish.   This was reported in Feb and asked that the test get reset. I should have two tries left.

I have been so discouraged that I gave up taking the other tests I studied for.

Additional_Comments__c: Training needs to evolve from "sage on the stage showing slides with the occasional exercise". Talking at people may be what we most commonly do, but it is also relatively uneffective--it's sort of the "waterfall" approach to teaching. Wouldn't things go better if we did blended learning, instead? Study the materials, then attend a class where you apply them with classmates--not as a quick diversion, but as a place where the instructors can guide and advise.

What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: While taking the SPC 5.0 upgrade exam for the first try, my wifi connection disconnected causing an error message on the exam page. I had already gone through 25 questions and my personal dashboard said I was 51% complete with the exam.  I messaged customer service about the issue and was told "You will have to take the exam over again. We are not able to offer free retakes when the issue is not on the side of Scaled Agile. There are two free attempts at the upgrade exam".  The issue here is not getting the full two try opportunity due to a technical difficulty out of my control. I reached out to Scaled Agile for assistance for a legitimate issue (with screenshots) and I received none. Instead, I was faced with possibly having to pay for an extra exam.  My experience leaves me disappointed. As an SPC, I pay approximately $900 a year for renewal/membership and as part of the SAFe family, I would expect a more professional "customer-centric" resolution. I am not happy with the lack of assistance I received. And this experience compels me to mention this on social media until the customer experience is improved.

Additional_Comments__c: The near-triple pricing to renew a single professional certification in a 2020-2021 transition for renewals, forcing the purchase of a full package (i.e. prior $100 cost compared to new $295 minimal, mandated cost to renew) is outrageous, particularly when considering the times economically right now with COVID-19 impacts, etc.  I have no idea why there is not a grandfathered renewal cost which, if needing to be increased for a single certification, is not nearly triple in price for a minimum required cost to renew just to keep the certification. This did not show customer centric needs, concerns or any sense of equity whatsoever, to just come out with this mandate between Thanksgiving and Christmas this year--end.  It would be excellent if there is some recant of this to allow for a grandfathered single-cert pricing which is a more modest increase in pricing.  Thank you.

Make it possible for me to have contact with a person.

This is a bizarre and indefensible disconnect. I've been a staunch advocate of SAFe for many years. I started back in the 3.0 days. But you all are becoming victims of your own success. 

If you  were consulting an enterprise and found out that they were holding their customers at arms-length, how would you respond? Honestly!

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
For me personally I have a challenging time with distance learning so the fact that business as usual queries interfered was inevitable as only in a classroom is the fact you are in training respected.

Also the pdfs ideally should be mailed out for people like myself who suffer with migraines particularly given the global pandemic.  Finally whilst I appreciate that there is a continuous learning cycle which feeds into improvements for SAFe, an actual handbook just like PMBOK, Prince2, etc. is a win-win for the learner particularly if their tutor is not as good as they would have wished.
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c:
For the 10 day free of charge extension to take an exam, it would be better if this was available to the learner from the outset rather than having to wait for the expiration date to be reached and then request it.  

Also with respect to "booking" an exam, the fact that it can be done 24-7 should be made clear.

Name: GetFeedback Survey Response: Net Promoter Score
Additional_Comments__c:
My experience with support (Emily) was good. My complaint is with the class and test. The Class - It clearly did not provide me with the information I needed to successfully pass the test. They guy just read through the notes, coupled with being on Zoom with little interactions with others. The Test - It's unreasonably tricky in wording. It's more of an exercise in figuring out poorly worded questions. And, some questions on it were not even covered in the class in depth enough to know the answers. You've created a test the is easy to fail. My last test I was 1 point off from passing. Now I only have 1 more try. Both the class and the test were huge time commitments for little reward. 

I've been PMP and Agile Scrum Master certified for more than decade. I've been applying SAFe principles for about as long, but yet the test is allusive? My money was not well spent.
Thanks for listening,
Susan Keithley
Senior Program/Project Manager at Ring/Amazon
What_can_SAI_make_easier_for_you__c: A phone call. But Emily was able to help me and answer questions.
